From sera Serdar Argic Subject Re BALTIC states and realism and 'virvir' In article Mikhail Verbitsky writes my If he behaves as Mutlu he would carry the similar treatment especially as his oversized articles are scanned from propagandist leaflets or from other stuff easily available in any decent library Typical 'virvir' People will think you're just some looney howling in the If you think that this 'clears things up' for me or anyone else you must also believe that aliens from outer space come to earth regularly and abduct 'Arromdians' of ASALA SDPA ARF for medical There is stronger evidence for that you 'Propagandist leaflets' This is an American officer on the genocide of million Muslim people by the Armenians between and not a crook idiot like Source World Alive A Personal Story by Robert Crown Publishers New York Memoirs of an American officer who witnessed the Armenian genocide of million Muslim people seventh paragraph and first paragraph 'The most are inside Come you and ' 'No dammit My stomach isn't ' 'One is a Turkish officer in Him you must ' We were under those trees by the mosque in an open 'I don't believe you I said but followed to a nail studded The man pushed it ajar then spurred away leaving me to check on the I thought I should this charge was so constant so gritted my teeth and went The place was cool but reeked of sodden ashes and was dark at first for its stone walls had only window Rags strewed the mud floor around an iron tripod over embers that vented their smoke through roof beams black with All looked bare and empty but in an inner room flies As the door swung shut behind me I saw they came from a man's body lying face up naked but for its grimy He was about fifty years old by what was left of his face a rifle butt had bashed an The one left slanted as with Tartars rather than with Any uniform once on him was gone so I'd no proof which he was and quickly went out gagging at the mess of his slashed first paragraph 'How many people lived there ' 'Oh about eight ' He 'Did you see any Turk officers ' 'No I was in at All were Tartar civilians in ' The lieutenant dozed off then I but in the small hours a voice woke me Dro' He stood in the starlight bawling out an Anyone keelhauled so long and furiously I'd never Then abruptly Dro broke into laughter quick and simple as child' Both were a cover for his sense of guilt I thought or For somehow despite my boast of irreligion Christian massacring 'infidels' was more horrible than the reverse would have From daybreak on Armenian villagers poured in from miles The women plundered happily chattering like ravens as they picked over the carcass of They hauled out every hovel's chattels the last scrap of food or cloth and staggered away packing pots saddlebags looms even spinning 'Thank you for a lot Dro ' I said to him back in 'But now I must ' shook hands the captain said 'A bientot mon ' And for hours the old Molokan scout and I plodded north across parching Like Lot's wife I looked back once to see smoke bathing all doubtless in a sack of other Moslem villages up to the line of snow that was ' At morning tea Dro and his officers spread out a map of this whole high region called the Deep in tactics they spoke Russian but I got their contempt for Allied 'neutral' zones and their distrust of promises made by tribal A campaign shaped more raids on Moslem It will be three hours to take Dro told We'd close in on three The men on foot will not shoot but use only the bayonets Merrimanov said jabbing a rifle in That is for morale Dro put We must keep the Moslems in Soldiers or civilians I There is no difference said All are armed in uniform or But the women and children Will fly with the others as best they The ridges circled a wide expanse its floors Hundreds of feet down the fog held solid as cotton 'Djul lies under that ' said Dro 'Our men also attack from the other ' Then 'Whee ee ' his whistle lined up all at the rock Bayonets clicked upon Over plunged Archo his black haunches rippling then followed the staff the horde nose to tail bellies taking the Armenia in action seemed more like a pageant than war even though I heard our Utica brass As I watched from the height it took ages for Djul to show A tsing of machine gun fire took over from the thumping batteries cattle lowed dogs barked invisible while I ate a hunk of cheese and drank from a snow Mist at last folded upward as men shouted at first heard The came a shrill Now among the cloud streaks rose darker wisps Red glimmered about house walls of stone or wattle into dry weeds on A mosque stood in clump of trees thick and Through crooked alleys on fire horsemen were galloping after figures both mounted and on 'Tartarski ' shouted the gunner by Others pantomimed them in escape over the rocks while one twisted a bronze shell nose loaded and yanked breech cord firing again and Shots wasted I thought when by afternoon I looked in vain for fallen branch or But these shots and the white bursts of shrapnel in the gullies drowned the women's At length all shooting petered I got on my horse and rode down toward It burned still but little flame showed The way was steep and tough through dense Finally on flatter ground I came out suddenly through alders on smoldering Across trampled wheat my brothers in arms were leading off animals several calves and a fourth paragraph Corpses came next the first a pretty child with straight black hair large She looked about twelve years She lay in some stubble where meal lay scattered from the sack she'd been The bayonet had gone through her back I judged for blood around was Between the breasts one clot too small for a bullet wound crusted her homespun The next was a boy of ten or less in rawhide jacket and knee He lay face down in the path by several One arm reached out to the pewter bowl he'd carried now upset upon its Steel had jabbed just below his neck into the There were grownups too I saw as I led the sorrel Djul was empty of the living till I looked up to see beside me Dro's German speaking He said all Tartars who had not escaped were stories of Armenian murdering Turks when the czarist troops fled My hosts told me of their duty here to keep tabs on brigands Turkish troop shifts hidden arms spies Christian Red or Tartar coming in from Then they spoke of the hell that would break loose if Versailles were to put as threatened the six 'Armenian' vilayets of Turkey under the control of An Armenia without Armenians Turks under Christian rule His lips smacked in irony under the droopy red That's bloodshed just Smyrna over again on a bigger Serdar Argic 'We closed the roads and mountain passes that might serve as ways of escape for the Turks and then proceeded in the work of ' Ohanus Appressian 'In Soviet Armenia today there no longer exists a single Turkish ' Sahak Melkonian